> Let's say that you have a list of features that need to be tested for
  our next release, how would you approach and understand what to test:

    - so basically, when i get a list of features to test, my approach would
      be first understand the requirements clearly

    - to begin with, i would go through the requirement documents or user stories
      to understand the functionality and expected behavior

    - then i would identify the critical and high-priority features, especially
      those that have maximum business impact

    - from my experience, this helps in focusing on what is most important for the release

    - next, i would break down the features into test scenarios and testcases,
     covering both positive and negative cases

    - at the same time, i would check dependencies between features, because some
      functionalities may impact others

    - then, i would decide which scenarios can be automated and which should be tested
      manually

    - i would also ensure regression coverage for existing functionalities to avoid
      any side effects

    - if needed, i would discuss with developers or product owners to clarify any doubts

    - so my approach is to understand prioritize, design test cases, and then
      execute efficiently to ensure quality coverage
